Package Funds

Class Entry

  • java.lang.Object
    • Funds.Entry
  • public class Entry
extends java.lang.Object

    Summary

    An Entry is the basic building block of the whole thing. It is a collection of datafields representing a single real-world monetary transaction.

    Every Entry made will have a corresponding Transfer -another entry with debits and credits reversed for the GAAP standard double-entry method of "balancing the books."

    The early stages of the plan have the Entry object corresponding to a single record in a relational database for compatibility with other accounting software concerns.

      • Entry

        public Entry​(java.time.LocalDate date,
             java.lang.String transactionID,
             java.lang.String Description,
             Account transfer,
             boolean reconcile,
             double debit,
             double credit)
        The full constructor to be used when all fields for a transaction are known (such as pulling from a relational database table)
        Parameters:
        date - The date on which the transaction was recognized
        transactionID - A human usable id for the transactions, may be different than database id
        Description - A brief description of the transaction
        transfer - The account into which the transaction will also be recorded for double-entry method of accounting
        reconcile - Traditionally this column was marked after the fact once a check had cleared the bank, I don't think this applies much in the modern world, but there's still plenty of ways a particular user could use a boolean value to mark or not in the transaction (personally I check this for expenses that may be reimbursed and unchecked for regular expenses, among other things)
        debit - The left column of the ledger: assets, dividends, and expenses are normal (increase with) debit accounts
        credit - The right column of the ledger: liabilities, revenue, and most equity are normal (increase with) credit accounts
